erstanding and misrepresentation of individual mystical experiences and fostered specious conclusions about cross-cultural comparability among them. Blum's hermeneutic invites the scholarly community to begin thinking about mystical experience in a new way-through the mystics' eyes. Zen and the Unspeakable God offers a sampling of the provocative results of this technique and an explanation of its implications for theories of consciousness and our contemporary understanding of the nature of mystical experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMysticism. 7aRELIGION / Mysticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271074719423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271074719.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK